he compiler because it's needed. The deterministic setup seems to only include dependencies, so I wonder if we should add scala-compiler. Is it something beyond the normal scaffold for a Scala test? It seems likely that the generated scaffold already includes the scala compiler. However, I notice that the library-specific POM only provides scala-reflect and actor. I need to clarify this to ensure everything’s in order.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating macro implementations**\\n\\nI’m thinking about macro implementations and their relationship to the compile classpath. It seems that the scala.reflect.macros.blackbox.Context symbols play a role in dependency resolution. It's interesting to consider how the compile engine interacts with the compiler itself during this process. I wonder about the implications for performance and usability in Scala. There’s definitely a lot to unpack here in terms of how it all works together!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n  \"summary\": \"The resolved 2.0.0-M1 artifact is a very small Scala macro/internal module whose POM marks required Pekko Actor and Scala Reflect dependencies as provided, so meaningful tests that load or exercise its remaining classes need those dependencies on the test classpath.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"dependency\",\n      \"coordinate\": \"org.apache.pekko:pekko-actor_2.13:2.0.0-M1\",\n      \"scope\": \"testImplementation\",\n      \"reason\": \"pekko-parsing_2.13:2.0.0-M1 declares pekko-actor_2.13 as provided, but its LogHelper API references org.apache.pekko.event.LoggingAdapter and Pekko annotation classes from that artifact.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"dependency\",\n      \"coordinate\": \"org.scala-lang:scala-reflect:2.13.18\",\n      \"scope\": \"testImplementation\",\n      \"reason\": \"The Scala 2 macro implementation in pekko-parsing_2.13:2.0.0-M1 references scala.reflect.macros.blackbox.Cont